Albanu was not sure what would happen if President Ilir Meta were to remain uncommitted on the matter. "I don't really know how the presidency works when it comes to constitutional conventions. So I don't know what the mechanisms are and who is entitled to what," he said.

But if Meta were to forego his right to declare the holiday, Albanu said, public pressure would probably mean it was marked anyway. “If 150 people gathered in front of the Casa de Cultură, and a big banner was left in front of the fountains you can bet everyone would be wearing Albanian flags and there would be at least something Albanian in the Casa," he said.

That represents a potential loss of tens of thousands lek in profit, even as the curfew’s scrapping earlier on Thursday provides a jolt to local tourism.

This state of affairs is the reason why the hotel comprises Billy Xiong and his partner, the 65-year-old Sejdini, feel more isolated than ever. The decision not to celebrate the event has galvanized Falasarna more than ever, apparently, with neighbors bickering over whether or not to run it, and supporters lining up along the street behind the hotel.
